WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.770 --> 00:00:06.540
&gt;&gt;Jeff: Hi everyone. I just want to welcome
Nathan here. A really pleasure to have him.

00:00:06.540 --> 00:00:10.230
The cookbooks are the most amazing cookbooks.
I don't even know whether to call them cookbooks

00:00:10.230 --> 00:00:13.690
that I've ever seen in my entire life. So
Nathan, can I first start out by saying do

00:00:13.690 --> 00:00:14.740
we call these cookbooks?

00:00:14.740 --> 00:00:16.170
&gt;&gt;Nathan: I call it--

00:00:16.170 --> 00:00:17.170
&gt;&gt;Jeff: Come on over here.

00:00:17.170 --> 00:00:22.390
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Yes. I call it a cookbook.

00:00:22.390 --> 00:00:23.390
&gt;&gt;Jeff: OK.

00:00:23.390 --> 00:00:24.960
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Now, it's in six volumes, admittedly.
But it started off in my mind as being one

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:27.260
volume. So I think of it as a cookbook.

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:30.480
&gt;&gt;Jeff: OK, so cookbook's all right. Well,
you got a little presentation.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:31.480
&gt;&gt;Nathan: OK.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:32.480
&gt;&gt;Jeff: I'll talk to you after that.

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:33.480
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Cool.

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:34.480
&gt;&gt;Jeff: And you're welcome.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:39.020
&gt;&gt;Nathan: OK, well thanks. So I just wanted
to tell you a little bit about the book. There's

00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:47.670
some fun facts we have on it. Six volumes,
2,438 pages, 1.1 million words. If you put

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:51.750
those in a single line of text, it will be
seven and a half miles long. It's not clear

00:00:51.750 --> 00:00:55.640
why you'd want to do that, but we thought
it was a cool statistic.

00:00:55.640 --> 00:01:01.230
We took 150,000 pictures and 3,200 of them
were good enough for the book. That's actually

00:01:01.230 --> 00:01:10.000
a good ratio, believe it or not. 1,522 recipes,
72 chefs from around the world gave us recipes

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.280
to use in the book. We had six research cooks,
full-time, for three years. Forty-four writers,

00:01:16.280 --> 00:01:19.369
editors, and art staff altogether.

00:01:19.369 --> 00:01:25.790
Forty pounds, and my favorite statistic, four
pounds of ink. When you get a book made, the

00:01:25.790 --> 00:01:30.350
printers make a blank book. And so I said,
"Well, gee, how close is this to the real

00:01:30.350 --> 00:01:34.030
book?" And they said, "Well, it'll be about
a half-inch thicker and four pounds heavier."

00:01:34.030 --> 00:01:38.529
And I said, "Why?" They said, "The ink." I
said, "You're kidding me."

00:01:38.529 --> 00:01:41.369
And they said, "Well, actually if you think
about it, a full page photo is about a thousandth

00:01:41.369 --> 00:01:46.289
of an inch of ink on it. Most of our pages
have photos. A thousandth of an inch times

00:01:46.289 --> 00:01:56.959
2,400." It's a thick block ink. And one of
the questions that I always get, so I'll just

00:01:56.959 --> 00:02:03.669
anticipate it here is, I'm a digital guy,
why am I talking about ink at all? Why don't

00:02:03.669 --> 00:02:07.020
I have it as a digital thing?

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:10.890
And there's two reasons. The first reason
is we made a decision about what platform

00:02:10.890 --> 00:02:16.100
to target about two years ago. And we figured
that's what it would take to do the first

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:21.830
version. And two years ago, there was no iPad.
There was only Kindle. And here's one of the

00:02:21.830 --> 00:02:27.460
pictures of the book. The Kindle version is
just pathetic 'cause it's small and it's black-and-white,

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:29.500
and it's not made for images.

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:35.840
The iPad version is better, but even so, you
would have to do amazing amounts of pan and

00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:41.470
scan and lots of work to take these very large
beautiful photos that we've done and try to

00:02:41.470 --> 00:02:47.190
adapt them for online. Eventually, we'll do
that. But to me, the reason to do it isn't

00:02:47.190 --> 00:02:50.700
because I wanna make a cheap version, or a
more portable version.

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:54.440
They both have some value. It's to make a
really cool version that uses interactivity

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:59.370
in lots of ways. Then, pretty much, it starts
being a software project and we'll get to

00:02:59.370 --> 00:03:04.700
it, but after the print version. The other
reason we did it, frankly, is that today,

00:03:04.700 --> 00:03:11.832
paper-based book is still the best way to
get this material out to the people that are

00:03:11.832 --> 00:03:12.832
interested in it.

00:03:12.832 --> 00:03:17.770
So we did a lot of work to make sure that
the quality was very high. You can see that

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:22.930
the industry standard is about 175 lines.
That's considered a very good half-tone screen

00:03:22.930 --> 00:03:26.370
for color reproduction. A really good art
book has 200.

00:03:26.370 --> 00:03:31.240
But there's no reason to have those fixed
grids anymore if you have computers. So we

00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:35.830
used something called stochastic screening.
Stocastic screening gives you just a ridiculously

00:03:35.830 --> 00:03:43.110
better-looking photo with effectively the
same printing technology. We also made sure

00:03:43.110 --> 00:03:48.980
we had great inks. So, industry standard inks
have lots of out of gamut colors.

00:03:48.980 --> 00:03:53.020
There's colors you can take a picture of with
a digital camera that you can't possibly reproduce

00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:56.709
in the ink. So here, you see the difference
all the gray areas in watered colors that

00:03:56.709 --> 00:04:02.690
don't reproduce. The reason we obsessed about
those things is that we think the presentation

00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:04.930
is important.

00:04:04.930 --> 00:04:09.720
If you went to the French Laundry or Manresa
or some other great restaurant and they served

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:14.830
you on paper plates, plastic forks, the food
would be the same but the presentation would

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:20.650
suffer. So we wanted to make sure that all
of the book was at the same quality level.

00:04:20.650 --> 00:04:25.939
So now I'm just gonna walk through a little
bit of what's in the book. Volume one is called

00:04:25.939 --> 00:04:28.750
"History and Fundamentals," and that's what
it's about.

00:04:28.750 --> 00:04:35.370
It's mostly material you'd never find in a
classic cookbook. But part of our idea here

00:04:35.370 --> 00:04:43.560
is there's a set of techniques and recipes
and methods and knowledge that the world had

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:49.020
developed over the course of the last 10,
20 years, which is very hard to learn. If

00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:52.229
you wanted to learn the techniques in the
book, you'd have to work at a restaurant like

00:04:52.229 --> 00:04:53.680
El Bulli in Spain.

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:59.389
I was there last week. Or the Fat Duck, I
was actually there this week. Actually, no,

00:04:59.389 --> 00:05:06.550
it was last week. Last week. Or, early last
week. So, you have to work there for a couple

00:05:06.550 --> 00:05:10.330
years before you would see some of the techniques
and even then you wouldn't get all of them.

00:05:10.330 --> 00:05:12.550
Some of the techniques come from food science
labs.

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:18.300
They come from all over the place. But I realized
that these techniques have been developed,

00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:22.550
but there was no good place to learn them.
There was no good place they all came together.

00:05:22.550 --> 00:05:27.319
And besides the actual techniques and the
mechanics of doing the cooking, there's lots

00:05:27.319 --> 00:05:31.189
of background information. What is the history
that motivates this?

00:05:31.189 --> 00:05:37.590
What's the science behind it? So, we cover
all kinds of things in there going all the

00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:43.289
way back, actually, from fire, all the way
up to the history of modern cooking. We cover

00:05:43.289 --> 00:05:48.889
things like--well, we've got some slides--we
cover things like the physics of food, how

00:05:48.889 --> 00:05:55.409
heat moves through food, so forth. Volume
Two is called "Techniques and Equipment."

00:05:55.409 --> 00:06:00.419
And so, it takes a different view of food.
It's about, as it says, techniques and equipment.

00:06:00.419 --> 00:06:06.309
And it starts with about a 200-page chapter.
So, almost a whole book, that's about traditional

00:06:06.309 --> 00:06:10.969
cooking. We go through every technique in
traditional cooking. We explain how it works,

00:06:10.969 --> 00:06:14.339
what are the physical principles behind it.

00:06:14.339 --> 00:06:19.669
'Cause a classic recipe tells you, "Do this.
Do this. Do this." And you get a result. And

00:06:19.669 --> 00:06:25.250
if you don't care why, or you don't want do
why, that's enough. But it's hard. If you

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:30.900
want to deviate from that recipe insight as
to why you're doing the things, is really

00:06:30.900 --> 00:06:31.900
important.

00:06:31.900 --> 00:06:37.370
So, the point of this volume is to say, "Here's
the insight behind how those techniques work,"

00:06:37.370 --> 00:06:44.039
so you can understand it well enough that
you can go cook in your own way, or if you're

00:06:44.039 --> 00:06:49.909
not into cooking, you can do it just because
you're curious about it. People ask me often,

00:06:49.909 --> 00:06:54.341
"Who is this book for? Is it for professionals?
Is it for home cooks?" And I always say it's

00:06:54.341 --> 00:06:59.780
for people who are passionate about food,
who are also curious about it. If you're not

00:06:59.780 --> 00:07:04.389
curious, then I don't have much of a proposition.
If you are, I think there's some cool stuff,

00:07:04.389 --> 00:07:11.770
even if you don't cook. Volume Three is called
"Animals and Plants." It takes an ingredient-oriented

00:07:11.770 --> 00:07:12.819
view of cooking.

00:07:12.819 --> 00:07:17.620
And, of course, the two most important ingredients
are plants and animals. So in this chapter,

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:23.300
we go through the structure of meat. We go
through why some cuts of meat are tough and

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:27.960
why some are not. We go through all of the
different aspects of plants and we have lots

00:07:27.960 --> 00:07:31.939
of recipes and techniques for dealing with
those.

00:07:31.939 --> 00:07:36.699
Some of them are classic. But mostly, we stayed
away from the classic techniques, 'cause lots

00:07:36.699 --> 00:07:40.050
of books have that, and we focused on the
really new interesting ones that lets you

00:07:40.050 --> 00:07:43.050
do stuff you couldn't any other way.

00:07:43.050 --> 00:07:47.909
I should say what I think "modernist cooking"
means. And we really view it as two things.

00:07:47.909 --> 00:07:53.449
One is a style of cooking that breaks some
of the traditional rules of cooking to let

00:07:53.449 --> 00:07:58.289
you do things you couldn't do any other way.
And the second is using brand new techniques

00:07:58.289 --> 00:08:02.149
that break those rules, even if you're achieving
a traditional outcome.

00:08:02.149 --> 00:08:09.539
So some of the food in the book is wild stuff,
like you'd find at some of these restaurants,

00:08:09.539 --> 00:08:15.729
like El Bulli in Spain that may not even look
like food or it looks like Klingon food. There's

00:08:15.729 --> 00:08:21.770
other things where the outcome is totally
traditional, either traditional Western food,

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:28.050
and we also have recipes in the book from
Chinese, Japanese, Indian, and other cuisines.

00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:32.130
So, it doesn't matter what the outcome is
so much as how you got there. And that's what

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:39.990
we focus on. Volume Four is called "Ingredients
and Preparations." Here, we look at ingredients,

00:08:39.990 --> 00:08:46.880
but ingredients other than meat versus plants.
Ingredients like thickeners. A huge part of

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:51.390
traditional cooking is about how to make a
sauce thick, or how to give body to a soup.

00:08:51.390 --> 00:08:55.372
There's some traditional ways to do that.
There's some modern ways. Gels are another

00:08:55.372 --> 00:09:01.540
topic we cover. Now, one kind of a gel is
cheese. Cheese is a protein gel made by coagulating

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:09.270
milk. Tofu is protein gel, made by coagulating
soy milk. So, we cover those. We cover gelatin,

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:13.520
but we also cover lots of brand new kinds
of gels because chefs have found ways to use

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:17.750
these gels in lots of interesting fashions.

00:09:17.750 --> 00:09:25.260
Finally, we cover coffee and wine but in a
somewhat irreverent way. Coffee is one of

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:32.090
the great beverages, but is really given short
shrift by most chefs. And I'm from Seattle

00:09:32.090 --> 00:09:36.470
and in Seattle we obsess over coffee. One
of the things I say in the book is a Michelin

00:09:36.470 --> 00:09:41.400
three-star restaurant is often serves coffee
that wouldn't be fit for a Seattle street

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:42.470
vendor.

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:47.930
And it's really true. There's a set of people
who obsess about food and will go to any length

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:52.270
to get the ultimate food. There's another
set that obsess about the ultimate coffee.

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:56.210
And pretty much, they're two different sets
of guys. And so, the point of this chapter

00:09:56.210 --> 00:10:01.960
is bring them together. We also have a chapter
on wine that takes a science-oriented view

00:10:01.960 --> 00:10:04.500
on wine, trying to demystify it.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:10.630
Wine is almost like a secular religion. There's
a whole ceremony associated with it. There's

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:15.650
this whole notion of connoisseurship. One
of the techniques we discuss in the book is

00:10:15.650 --> 00:10:17.140
something we call "hyper decanting."

00:10:17.140 --> 00:10:21.780
This is where you take a bottle of wine, particularly
a younger red wine, you should all try this

00:10:21.780 --> 00:10:28.560
at home, you pour it into a blender and you
hit frappe and you frappe the hell out of

00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:33.430
it for 30 seconds or so. Let it calm down.
Then, pour it in. It achieves what decanting

00:10:33.430 --> 00:10:37.120
achieves, but way more so. Now there's two
reasons to do this.

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:41.370
One, is for a younger red wine, it makes it
much more drinkable. And in most cases, in

00:10:41.370 --> 00:10:46.960
a blind taste test, we preferred the hyper
decanted to ordinary decanting it right from

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:51.260
the bottle. But the other reason we do it
is it freaks wine people out so much.

00:10:51.260 --> 00:10:52.260
[laughter]

00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:56.420
Oh, my God. You go and you pour this great
bottle of wine into the blender and hit the

00:10:56.420 --> 00:11:02.530
switch and they look at you like you're a
complete lunatic. But it works.

00:11:02.530 --> 00:11:05.170
[laughter]

00:11:05.170 --> 00:11:11.500
So, Volume Five is the first volume in the
whole book that actually looks like a cookbook.

00:11:11.500 --> 00:11:18.120
We've got about 1,500 recipes in the book.
The "Plated-Dish Recipes" volume takes about

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:25.180
50 recipes and goes--49, I guess--and goes
in-depth in them to give not just the main

00:11:25.180 --> 00:11:30.510
thing you're cooking, but the garnishes on
the plate and in most cases, the entire rest

00:11:30.510 --> 00:11:31.690
of the meal.

00:11:31.690 --> 00:11:37.600
So as an example, we went nuts on barbecue
'cause I love Southern barbecue. I actually

00:11:37.600 --> 00:11:42.930
competed once in World Championship of Barbecue.
And we actually won. But not due to me. I

00:11:42.930 --> 00:11:48.410
was like the lowest ranking guy on the team.
So we developed nine barbecue sauces for the

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:51.690
book. And then, we developed recipes for cornbread
and baked beans.

00:11:51.690 --> 00:11:59.560
Essentially, an entire barbecue meal. And
that's one of those 50 things in here. Now,

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:06.050
one of the things that we thought was a huge
value to our book was the use of cool pictures

00:12:06.050 --> 00:12:12.240
to both illustrate things you couldn't otherwise
show people, and to get people excited about

00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:15.260
concepts that might seem a little dull and
boring.

00:12:15.260 --> 00:12:21.510
So this is from our section on canning. And
if you have an acidic vegetable, in this case,

00:12:21.510 --> 00:12:25.870
pickled vegetables, you can do what's called
"boiling water canning." And this is our photo

00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:31.630
for boiling water canning. We use this idea
of a cutaway throughout the book to try to

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:37.060
illustrate the magic view of what's happening
in your food while you cook it.

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:41.660
As you can see, we not only cut the pot in
half, we cut the jars in half, too, 'cause

00:12:41.660 --> 00:12:51.770
what the hell. We have lots of photos in all
kinds of ways. This is a centrifuge jar. We

00:12:51.770 --> 00:12:59.850
use a lot of interesting equipment in cooking.
A centrifuge subjects the liquid to a force

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:03.870
equivalent to about 40,000 times Earth's normal
gravity.

00:13:03.870 --> 00:13:07.510
That causes things to separate out. In this
case, this is a sauce we made. This is actually

00:13:07.510 --> 00:13:14.330
a Hungarian goulash. It separated into eight
layers by density. Now, you might say, "Why

00:13:14.330 --> 00:13:18.380
do you want to do that?" I'm sure that there's
lots of reasons.

00:13:18.380 --> 00:13:24.130
You can take all kinds of food products and
spin it in these centrifuges to achieve a

00:13:24.130 --> 00:13:29.200
clear consomme, or some other thing like that
that you just couldn't get any other way.

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:34.200
That also brings up a question. How much of
this can you do at home? I say out of 1,500

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:36.780
recipes, at least half are easy to do in the
home.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:41.121
If you're willing to buy a little bit of equipment,
but nothing too exotic, just stuff you can

00:13:41.121 --> 00:13:46.870
get at Williams Sonoma, or some other mall
cooking store, it's maybe 75 percent of the

00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:53.260
book. And the last 25, good luck because that's
when you need to get liquid nitrogen dewars.

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:54.260
[laughter]

00:13:54.260 --> 00:13:58.770
No, seriously. We have a whole section, "Cooking
with Liquid Nitrogen." It's fantastic. Unless

00:13:58.770 --> 00:14:03.180
you make stuff super cold, without making
it wet. Whereas ice, of course, doesn't let

00:14:03.180 --> 00:14:08.210
you do that. And that last 25 percent, you
can do at home.

00:14:08.210 --> 00:14:15.820
I do it all at home. But it's gonna require
a little bit of effort. Here's something where

00:14:15.820 --> 00:14:22.670
we're using a torch to sear things. This is
pomegranate seeds. Here's another one of our

00:14:22.670 --> 00:14:33.140
cutaway photos. This is a traditional pot
roast in a Dutch oven. This is enzyme-peeled

00:14:33.140 --> 00:14:37.960
grapefruit. It turns out, there's an enzyme
called Peelzym.

00:14:37.960 --> 00:14:45.520
And you can soak citrus in it and it only
attacks a special pectin molecule that's in

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:52.360
the outer thing. So you soak it in there and
it all pulls off. But it also makes it look

00:14:52.360 --> 00:15:02.180
cool. This is potato starch in a potato. The
purple things are the actual starch granules

00:15:02.180 --> 00:15:10.041
and the blue lines are the cell walls of the
potato. Here's an example spread where we

00:15:10.041 --> 00:15:11.480
show what's going on.

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:16.160
This is actually the first picture I took
for the book to see if this cutaway thing

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:22.170
would work. And it kind of did. This is steaming
broccoli. So all of the little text boxes

00:15:22.170 --> 00:15:27.810
around the outside explain what's going on.
What's happening with the boiling? What's

00:15:27.810 --> 00:15:35.390
happening with the condensation? How is it
heating? Up in the corner, there's a box that

00:15:35.390 --> 00:15:39.140
describes the difference between boiling and
steaming.

00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:43.890
In theory, steaming ought to have much higher
heat transfer. In practice, it actually doesn't

00:15:43.890 --> 00:15:48.529
for a bunch of reasons we explain in the text.
It's actually slightly slower to steam broccoli

00:15:48.529 --> 00:15:56.090
than it is to boil it. Here's our wok cutaway.
Now, we discovered why people don't cook with

00:15:56.090 --> 00:15:57.090
half a wok, here.

00:15:57.090 --> 00:15:58.980
[laughter]

00:15:58.980 --> 00:16:03.840
This caught fire three times while we were
doing it, because there's actually no trick

00:16:03.840 --> 00:16:08.779
to this. We were cooking with a wok that was
cut in half. Now, not exactly half. We cut

00:16:08.779 --> 00:16:13.810
about a third of it off, but the oil kept
going in the fire and it would catch fire.

00:16:13.810 --> 00:16:18.670
But we had this great motto: It only has to
look good for a thousandth of a second.

00:16:18.670 --> 00:16:19.670
[laughter]

00:16:19.670 --> 00:16:23.380
And so, a lot of these photos, people say,
"Well, what's the trick? Aren't you using

00:16:23.380 --> 00:16:28.560
Photoshop?" And well, every digital photographer
uses Photoshop, but mostly the trick is willingness

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:36.690
to make a mess. Here's that same picture now
where we can zoom in and see a bunch of the

00:16:36.690 --> 00:16:39.730
different text things explaining it.

00:16:39.730 --> 00:16:44.070
Here's our barbecue cutaway. So those coals
are just sitting there at the edge. That's

00:16:44.070 --> 00:16:47.470
really cut in half and they kept falling off,
but again, it only has to look good for a

00:16:47.470 --> 00:16:52.980
thousandth of a second. What we explain here
is all of the things that go on in grilling

00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:55.980
hamburgers. And it turns out, there's lots
of interesting dynamics.

00:16:55.980 --> 00:17:02.490
Those drops of fat that fall are crucial because
those flare-ups produce most of the characteristic

00:17:02.490 --> 00:17:07.030
grilled flavor. You get a different flavor
from grilling like this than if you broil

00:17:07.030 --> 00:17:10.660
it from the top, even with the same amount
of heat. The reason is, from the top you don't

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:16.170
get those fat fires happening. This is how
you cut things in half.

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:23.339
This is our machine shop. My company has a
whole laboratory where we prototype inventions

00:17:23.339 --> 00:17:28.731
that we come up with. And this is our shop.
And we decided to build our kitchen laboratory,

00:17:28.731 --> 00:17:32.600
where we made the book, right around the corner
from this. So whenever we wanted to cut something

00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:35.180
in half, we come over here.

00:17:35.180 --> 00:17:40.130
Here is a short video. This is a wire EDM
machine. And we've got a pot coming in. Wire

00:17:40.130 --> 00:17:46.559
EDM uses very high electrical current. It
makes tiny sparks. You can see them there.

00:17:46.559 --> 00:17:51.730
The whole thing happens underwater, believe
it or not. And those tiny sparks jumping off

00:17:51.730 --> 00:17:56.130
this brass wire, actually will cut any kind
of a metal or conductive surface.

00:17:56.130 --> 00:18:01.920
So you come out and voila. We have cut the
pot in half. We had other machines we would

00:18:01.920 --> 00:18:08.980
use to cut glass in half or all kinds of other
things. So, there's some of the things cut

00:18:08.980 --> 00:18:13.810
in half. Actually, we have two halves of one
of the best kitchens in the world. They're

00:18:13.810 --> 00:18:21.120
just not together anymore. You can see with
the one pot there, a technique we used to

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:24.771
keep stuff in, we glue a piece of Pyrex in
front of the pot.

00:18:24.771 --> 00:18:28.640
Now that gives you a little glue line, but
there, that's where Photoshop is handy 'cause

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:32.460
you can photograph the other side of the pot.
When you cut it in half, you get two halves.

00:18:32.460 --> 00:18:37.880
So you photograph the edge in the same position
and then you can swap it in. It's a lot like

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:41.650
a Hollywood movie where a guy flies through
the air supported by a wire, and then they

00:18:41.650 --> 00:18:47.230
digitally take the wire out.

00:18:47.230 --> 00:18:52.380
Here's one of our nerdier parts of the book.
This is our chapter on heat and energy. So,

00:18:52.380 --> 00:18:56.990
we have partial differential equations in
the cookbook. The cookbook has the strange

00:18:56.990 --> 00:19:01.809
distinction that I wrote thousands of lines
of code to write the cookbook, 'cause we used

00:19:01.809 --> 00:19:09.160
lots of computer simulations to understand
things like heat conductivity, like the diffusion

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:10.160
of a brine.

00:19:10.160 --> 00:19:14.960
If you brine a meat, that's also run by a
diffusion equation. So, tons of code were

00:19:14.960 --> 00:19:24.760
written to write this book and here's some
of the equations. Here's another example of

00:19:24.760 --> 00:19:30.630
things. Suppose you've got a barbecue. Well,
as you move away from the hot surface, the

00:19:30.630 --> 00:19:35.520
heat falls down, right? And if you move far
enough away, there's hardly any heat at all.

00:19:35.520 --> 00:19:41.920
But what does that curve actually look like?
Well, we calculated it. Most of the heat is

00:19:41.920 --> 00:19:46.610
not coming from hot air there. It's coming
from infrared rays and so, you can calculate

00:19:46.610 --> 00:19:52.130
how much radiation is emitted. It's important
not only for how the heat varies as you move

00:19:52.130 --> 00:19:56.140
vertically, but how even is the heat as you
move side to side.

00:19:56.140 --> 00:20:00.540
And that funny horn-shaped thing is what we
call the "sweet spot." That's the zone for

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:05.309
which the side to side heat variation isn't
more than about ten percent. So, if you want

00:20:05.309 --> 00:20:12.270
the best results, that's where you should
be grilling. Here's an example of a step-by-step

00:20:12.270 --> 00:20:17.170
technique. This is one for making hamburger,
believe it or not.

00:20:17.170 --> 00:20:22.720
One of the philosophies we had with the book
is that any dish that is worthy of a cook's

00:20:22.720 --> 00:20:28.470
attention, is worthy of refinement. So we
set out to make the ultimate hamburger. Now,

00:20:28.470 --> 00:20:32.210
our idea of the ultimate hamburger may not
be yours. And you might wanna just run to

00:20:32.210 --> 00:20:34.960
the In-N-Out Burger and get something really
quick and that's perfectly fine.

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:42.620
But if you care about a burger, you can lavish
as much care on a burger as you could on some

00:20:42.620 --> 00:20:48.100
otherwise very fancy French dish that involves
foie gras and 50 ingredients. In this case,

00:20:48.100 --> 00:20:53.580
the key is a technique in how you grind the
burger. 'Cause believe it or not, the alignment

00:20:53.580 --> 00:20:55.270
of the grain matters.

00:20:55.270 --> 00:21:00.460
So what we're doing here is we're trying to
align the grain so that if you see the cut-in-half

00:21:00.460 --> 00:21:05.980
burger, all of those tubes of meat that get
pushed out of the grinder, are all vertical.

00:21:05.980 --> 00:21:10.530
And that means when you bite it, it crumbles
better.

00:21:10.530 --> 00:21:14.650
And crumbling, or being very tender, is important
in the sandwich 'cause when you pull away,

00:21:14.650 --> 00:21:18.170
you don't want to pull away and leave the
burger pulled out of the rest of it. It's

00:21:18.170 --> 00:21:25.580
gotta all come down directly. So here's the
close-up of the technique of how you align

00:21:25.580 --> 00:21:31.980
the grain. It's very simple. But once you've
tried it both ways, this way is better.

00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:37.600
Here's the actual burger. It's a wonder what
you can do when you suspend gravity. Here,

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:42.420
in the book, we actually cover the recipe
for everything that you see there. The bun,

00:21:42.420 --> 00:21:50.560
the sauce, the lettuce is infused with smoke
because that gives you a cool smoky thing

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:55.460
while it stays crunchy. Not only do we show
you how to grind the burger, but what mix

00:21:55.460 --> 00:21:57.390
of meats to use for the burger.

00:21:57.390 --> 00:22:02.830
And we even know of a cool technique for cooking
the burger that involves liquid nitrogen.

00:22:02.830 --> 00:22:07.240
Our idea of an ultimate burger is that it's
perfectly medium rare, edge to edge, but really,

00:22:07.240 --> 00:22:13.690
really crispy on the outside. So we do that
by cooking it sous vide, in an unsealed bag,

00:22:13.690 --> 00:22:17.720
to a medium rare. Then we put it in liquid
nitrogen for about 45 seconds.

00:22:17.720 --> 00:22:23.870
Then we put it into a deep fryer. Now, the
deep fryer makes the outside super crispy.

00:22:23.870 --> 00:22:29.050
The point of the liquid nitrogen is that it
freezes and chills enough of the burger that

00:22:29.050 --> 00:22:33.720
it doesn't overheat the inside, so you don't
get these big bands of gray. Normally, if

00:22:33.720 --> 00:22:41.150
you cook something under high heat, you get
a big band of gray and we wanted to avoid

00:22:41.150 --> 00:22:42.390
that.

