00:30:22.790 --> 00:30:23.790
better.

00:30:23.790 --> 00:30:24.790
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Yes.

00:30:24.790 --> 00:30:26.710
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #1: I would like to
hear you expand a little bit. It sounds like

00:30:26.710 --> 00:30:27.710
you cook one--

00:30:27.710 --> 00:30:28.710
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Right.

00:30:28.710 --> 00:30:31.880
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #1: in a sous vide
container and that that heated up significantly

00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:32.880
faster.

00:30:32.880 --> 00:30:40.010
&gt;&gt;Nathan: OK. So let me give a little background.
So, if you Google "barbecue stall," S-T-A-L-L,

00:30:40.010 --> 00:30:46.220
you'll get a few links that are about a stall
that sells barbecue, like at a state fair.

00:30:46.220 --> 00:30:51.350
But if you say "barbecue stall temperature,"
you'll get literally thousands of hits, because

00:30:51.350 --> 00:30:54.530
one of the great mysteries of barbecue is
called "the stall."

00:30:54.530 --> 00:30:59.240
And here's what happens. You cook a brisket,
or a pork shoulder or whole hog, some big

00:30:59.240 --> 00:31:03.151
piece of meat, and you watch the temperature.
And initially, you put it in and the temperature

00:31:03.151 --> 00:31:09.150
increases, increases, increases, then it stalls.
And it's way below the temperature of the

00:31:09.150 --> 00:31:15.880
air in the barbecue. And it stays stalled
for hours, two hours, four hours, sometimes

00:31:15.880 --> 00:31:16.880
even more.

00:31:16.880 --> 00:31:21.679
Then, it starts going back up again. So, what
the hell is the stall? And these thousands

00:31:21.679 --> 00:31:26.570
of pages on the 'net are all about people
trying to explain what the stall is about.

00:31:26.570 --> 00:31:31.669
And the usual explanation is that what's happening
is the collagen in the meat is being converted

00:31:31.669 --> 00:31:36.240
into gelatin and that process is what makes
tough meat tender.

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:42.130
It's also what makes stock that you cook for
a long time, like veal stock, unctuous and

00:31:42.130 --> 00:31:47.789
rich. And it makes it gel up if you let it
get cold. Well, that process was surely happening,

00:31:47.789 --> 00:31:53.740
but I realized there was nowhere near enough
energy in that reaction, that it could take

00:31:53.740 --> 00:31:57.120
all of that heat out. And so it had to be
something else.

00:31:57.120 --> 00:32:01.630
So, I realized there's only one thing that
it could possibly be and that's the evaporation

00:32:01.630 --> 00:32:07.559
of water. That in fact, what you're doing
is you are drying out your big piece of meat

00:32:07.559 --> 00:32:11.080
and it's something called evaporative cooling.
The same reason you feel cool when you get

00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:15.799
out of a pool, unless it's a 100 percent humidity
outside.

00:32:15.799 --> 00:32:20.309
So in fact, what was happening is that you
would go through a long period of drying.

00:32:20.309 --> 00:32:26.511
Then as soon as the outside was dry, then
the temperature could start going back up.

00:32:26.511 --> 00:32:33.260
So to prove that, we did an experiment where
we took one brisket, cut it in half. One of

00:32:33.260 --> 00:32:36.970
them, we sealed in a plastic bag, just so
there would be no evaporation.

00:32:36.970 --> 00:32:40.760
You could also seal it in aluminum foil. We
tried that, too, and it doesn't make any difference.

00:32:40.760 --> 00:32:46.340
And so we put them both in there. We had temperature
probes stuck all over both of them. And we

00:32:46.340 --> 00:32:51.870
put them into a convection oven. That let
us control the temperature better than a real

00:32:51.870 --> 00:32:56.990
barbecue. We could have also done a barbecue,
but the same thing would happen.

00:32:56.990 --> 00:33:03.840
Sure enough, the one that was uncovered stalled
for about two and a half hours and then it

00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:11.970
went back up. The one which was covered up,
no stall at all. And any collagen, anything

00:33:11.970 --> 00:33:17.570
like that, would be in both of them. So, we
sort of, I think definitively, showed that.

00:33:17.570 --> 00:33:21.059
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #1: Was there more
humidity in the oven when you cooked the one

00:33:21.059 --> 00:33:22.059
that was uncovered?

00:33:22.059 --> 00:33:26.910
&gt;&gt;Nathan: So we also had a thermometer in
the oven, and what's called a wet-bulb thermometer.

00:33:26.910 --> 00:33:32.230
So this measures the actual humidity. So what
happens is the humidity of the oven initially

00:33:32.230 --> 00:33:37.750
goes up, then over a period of time the humidity
goes down because there's some air venting

00:33:37.750 --> 00:33:39.250
out of the oven.

00:33:39.250 --> 00:33:44.419
So, this is all about rates. You're gonna
evaporate from a certain rate in the meat

00:33:44.419 --> 00:33:48.860
until you get such a dry crust on the meat
that you can't evaporate at that same rate

00:33:48.860 --> 00:33:52.070
anymore. Meanwhile, you have another rate,
which is the rate at which water is coming

00:33:52.070 --> 00:33:56.170
out of the oven. Now one of the really funny
things about this is when you're in the middle

00:33:56.170 --> 00:34:00.610
of the stall, the traditional wisdom is slather
more sauce on.

00:34:00.610 --> 00:34:05.990
But this is like trying to heat something
while you run a garden hose on it. OK? The

00:34:05.990 --> 00:34:10.070
more sauce you put on, the more there is for
evaporation. So instead of stalling for two

00:34:10.070 --> 00:34:13.050
hours, you can make it stall for as long as
you want it if you just kept pouring water

00:34:13.050 --> 00:34:14.050
on it.

00:34:14.050 --> 00:34:16.490
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #1: So the take-away
I was looking for is, I use dry rub--

00:34:16.490 --> 00:34:17.490
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Yup.

00:34:17.490 --> 00:34:19.930
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #1: instead of sauce
when I'm cooking. Is that compatible with

00:34:19.930 --> 00:34:22.060
keeping it inside of plastic?

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:23.060
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Sure.

00:34:23.060 --> 00:34:24.060
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #1: OK.

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:27.281
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Sure, but the other thing is, you
have to--. There's different things you want

00:34:27.281 --> 00:34:31.520
to achieve at different parts of cooking the
barbecue. So, our high-tech approach to barbecue

00:34:31.520 --> 00:34:35.550
is we smoke. We typically put a dry rub on.

00:34:35.550 --> 00:34:40.369
Then we smoke at very low temperature. Then
we cook it sous vide. And then at the end,

00:34:40.369 --> 00:34:45.359
we'll either smoke it again to create a bark,
or crust, on the outside, or our best technique

00:34:45.359 --> 00:34:52.419
is again, liquid nitrogen and a deep fryer.
So you haven't lived until you've had liquid

00:34:52.419 --> 00:34:53.419
nitrogen, deep-fried spareribs.

00:34:53.419 --> 00:34:55.360
&gt;&gt;Jeff: Our cooks, they're just totally wondering
how we're gonna do this and how we're gonna

00:34:55.360 --> 00:34:56.470
bring in liquid nitrogen. So one thing after
Microsoft--

00:34:56.470 --> 00:34:57.470
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Yeah.

00:34:57.470 --> 00:35:05.280
&gt;&gt;Jeff: why did you get interested in cooking
and how did you learn all this?

00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:07.810
&gt;&gt;Nathan: So, I was interested in cooking
my whole life.

00:35:07.810 --> 00:35:08.810
&gt;&gt;Jeff: OK.

00:35:08.810 --> 00:35:12.840
&gt;&gt;Nathan: When I was nine, I told my mother
I was gonna cook Thanksgiving dinner and she

00:35:12.840 --> 00:35:16.840
let me. I went to the library. I got this
whole stack of books out and, by God, I cooked

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:18.340
