00:38:11.790 --> 00:38:14.650
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #2: Yeah, my question
would be what are the top three things that

00:38:14.650 --> 00:38:19.970
everybody does wrong that the average home
cook could do just slightly differently and

00:38:19.970 --> 00:38:21.050
make a big difference?

00:38:21.050 --> 00:38:27.360
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Well, "wrong" is a tough thing.
But I'll give you a couple quick tips. I'm

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:31.340
not saying anyone's gonna cook wrong. But
the first one is, if you're making an omelet

00:38:31.340 --> 00:38:36.950
or scrambled eggs, there's a tremendous trick
to heed. If you're making a three-egg omelet

00:38:36.950 --> 00:38:39.190
or scrambled egg, throw one egg white away.

00:38:39.190 --> 00:38:44.960
They're cheap. So, two whole eggs, one yolk.
Enormously improves the texture. There are

00:38:44.960 --> 00:38:51.140
people who add butter or cream. You can also
do that. But you get much of the same improvement

00:38:51.140 --> 00:38:57.180
and texture as butter or cream just by throwing
one white away. The second thing is, it's

00:38:57.180 --> 00:38:59.250
best if you cook it under extremely low heat.

00:38:59.250 --> 00:39:04.370
So we cook it in a water bath, or we cook
it in a steam oven. And we cook it to exactly

00:39:04.370 --> 00:39:10.550
71 Centigrade, 165 Fahrenheit. You can vary
that a little bit depending, for scrambled

00:39:10.550 --> 00:39:16.300
eggs. A little bit hotter for an omelet. And
that lets you do--. Just those two simple

00:39:16.300 --> 00:39:22.150
things, temperature control and throwing one
egg white away, totally changes omelets. So,

00:39:22.150 --> 00:39:23.840
not everything but it's one trick.

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:29.230
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #3: Hi. So, question
about coffee--

00:39:29.230 --> 00:39:30.230
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Yeah.

00:39:30.230 --> 00:39:32.540
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #3: being from Seattle,
