00:39:46.600 --> 00:39:50.530
in Seattle about 20 years ago and now has
broadened out. So there's lots of cool people

00:39:50.530 --> 00:39:55.040
around the world. There's a great guy in London
doing cool coffee work. There's a fantastic

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:58.410
guy in Norway doing cool coffee work.

00:39:58.410 --> 00:40:02.260
Some of these people I've met and a lot of
them I only know over the internet. But the

00:40:02.260 --> 00:40:08.280
state-of-the-art coffee techniques are all
attention to detail things. I'd love to say

00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:12.421
there's a magic machine, but mostly it's super
good temperature control in the machines.

00:40:12.421 --> 00:40:16.320
There's a machine called a Synesso, made in
Seattle, which is a fantastic espresso machine.

00:40:16.320 --> 00:40:23.780
La Marzocco also has a pretty cool one. The
next interesting thing after good temperature

00:40:23.780 --> 00:40:33.190
control, so that means using something called
a PID--a proportional integral differential

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:37.690
temperature controller--anyway, it controls
temperature perfectly. The next thing is something

00:40:37.690 --> 00:40:42.080
called pressure profiling. And that's just
now happening.

00:40:42.080 --> 00:40:46.440
There's only a few machines. There's probably
no really good machine on the market yet that

00:40:46.440 --> 00:40:50.530
really, in a broad way, does pressure profiling.
What that allows you to do is to say the pressure

00:40:50.530 --> 00:40:55.020
you make when you make espresso. That goes
over set of--. Now, that's for espresso. Then

00:40:55.020 --> 00:40:59.540
there's a half a dozen other things that I
could go into about making the ideal espresso.

00:40:59.540 --> 00:41:05.130
For regular coffee, my favorite way to make
it is something called an AeroPress. And it's

00:41:05.130 --> 00:41:12.690
like a $29 piece of plastic that you buy on
Amazon. And you know those Super Soaker kinds

00:41:12.690 --> 00:41:19.400
of--? Well, it's like a Super Soaker, but
you put it over your coffee cup and you heat

00:41:19.400 --> 00:41:27.420
the water to exactly 175 degrees, medium grind,
but a drip grind, not an espresso grind.

00:41:27.420 --> 00:41:35.460
And there's a few other things. You wait for
30 seconds and then you plunge it. It's fantastic.

00:41:35.460 --> 00:41:38.350
