&gt;&gt;Nathan: Yup.

00:41:43.250 --> 00:41:44.770
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #4: So, could you go
into how you selected these folks in the Dream

00:41:44.770 --> 00:41:47.400
Team? And what are they doing now that the
book is out?

00:41:47.400 --> 00:41:56.930
&gt;&gt;Nathan: So, I realized if I hadn't written
software, I never would have written this

00:41:56.930 --> 00:42:04.130
book because most books are one person's singular
vision. And that's really what defines those

00:42:04.130 --> 00:42:09.220
books. And one person can write a piece of
software, but usually the best software isn't

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:13.560
written by a single person, 'cause a), there's
only so much a single person can do.

00:42:13.560 --> 00:42:18.660
Usually, a small team. A really big team has
a hard time equaling the productivity of a

00:42:18.660 --> 00:42:23.859
smaller team. And so, we always wanted like,
six to ten people. It was the ideal size software

00:42:23.859 --> 00:42:28.180
team in my view. But I also wasn't afraid
of having a team like that and even having

00:42:28.180 --> 00:42:31.800
a larger team of people around it because
I wasn't afraid of that.

00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:38.349
As soon as I realized that this book--. Scale
was an important thing for the book. If I

00:42:38.349 --> 00:42:44.170
got all of these topics together in one place,
I could really achieve something because people

00:42:44.170 --> 00:42:49.040
could learn it all in one place. But if you
only have half of them, you did a little something.

00:42:49.040 --> 00:42:52.270
But people still have to scramble to find
the other half.

00:42:52.270 --> 00:42:57.400
So I decided at some point, "Hey, this is
gonna be a team project." So I hired a guy

00:42:57.400 --> 00:43:01.431
who'd worked at the Fat Duck. It was this
fantastic restaurant in England. Now, he'd

00:43:01.431 --> 00:43:05.810
been a chemist in a graduate student at the
University of Washington prior to that. So,

00:43:05.810 --> 00:43:11.890
he also understood science a lot. I hired
an editor. Actually, even before I decided

00:43:11.890 --> 00:43:13.480
to do the book, from "Scientific American."

00:43:13.480 --> 00:43:18.340
I made him the editor-in-chief and then we
just picked people one at a time. All the

00:43:18.340 --> 00:43:22.180
photos were taken by me and my assistant.
Although, my assistant wound up taking 90

00:43:22.180 --> 00:43:30.080
percent of them. And he was a guy who answered
