00:48:58.920 --> 00:49:05.712
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #7: Hello. Thank you
for your presentation. I'm a fellow physicist

00:49:05.712 --> 00:49:07.470
and you talk a lot about temperature control.

00:49:07.470 --> 00:49:08.470
&gt;&gt;Nathan: Yup.

00:49:08.470 --> 00:49:11.820
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #7: I would like it
if you could expand a little bit on the spectrum

00:49:11.820 --> 00:49:17.970
of actually the heat-producing elements in
barbecues, or kitchens, because what I don't

00:49:17.970 --> 00:49:24.470
understand when I came to the U.S. and I saw
people grilling on a flame, how does that

00:49:24.470 --> 00:49:28.150
change the spectrum? And are there benefits
to doing that?

00:49:28.150 --> 00:49:36.150
&gt;&gt;Nathan: OK. So, the simple answer to that
is no. But here's the thing. Most traditional

00:49:36.150 --> 00:49:41.630
approaches to cooking start with a very high
heat source. Originally, that was a fire.

00:49:41.630 --> 00:49:46.990
But you never want to cook the food as hot
as the fire is.

00:49:46.990 --> 00:49:52.660
OK, it would burn. The other thing is most
food is mostly water. And as a result, you

00:49:52.660 --> 00:49:56.250
can't actually make the food hotter than the
boiling point of water until you've dried

00:49:56.250 --> 00:50:02.849
out the outside at least. So a typical cooking
technique says, "I have this super high heat

00:50:02.849 --> 00:50:08.940
and then I cook with it by timing, very carefully,
how long I put it in that high heat and how

00:50:08.940 --> 00:50:10.810
long I take it off."

00:50:10.810 --> 00:50:14.620
That's true whether you're cooking in a pot,
you're cooking on a grill, you're cooking

00:50:14.620 --> 00:50:21.870
on other things. The more modern approach,
which we describe in the book, just says,

00:50:21.870 --> 00:50:27.160
"No, screw it. You should cook with low temperature."
So, if you want to cook meat medium rare,

00:50:27.160 --> 00:50:31.210
that means you wanna make the meat about 130
Fahrenheit.

00:50:31.210 --> 00:50:37.691
So, the way we do that, we cook at about 132
Fahrenheit. So we use a very low temperature

00:50:37.691 --> 00:50:43.151
source. Low temperature steam or water in
a water bath. It takes longer for the heat

00:50:43.151 --> 00:50:48.320
to soak in, but never can overcook it. If
you forget it an hour, it doesn't matter.

00:50:48.320 --> 00:50:49.900
If you're a little bit early, it doesn't matter
either.

00:50:49.900 --> 00:50:54.060
You're only off by a fraction of a degree.
So that's a very fundamental thing. Now, you

00:50:54.060 --> 00:51:00.200
ask about grilling. Grilling is cooking with
infrared rays. Those infrared rays mostly

00:51:00.200 --> 00:51:06.369
come over other hot things. And simply a gas
flame is a poor way to do it. That's why most

00:51:06.369 --> 00:51:10.410
good gas grills have a metal plate in there
that the flame goes on.

00:51:10.410 --> 00:51:18.160
And it's the heat from that plate that is
going on to your food. In the case of barbecue

00:51:18.160 --> 00:51:23.520
coals, what looks like fire around them is
actually little particles that are being heated

00:51:23.520 --> 00:51:30.339
up incandescence. And the blueness of the
flame has nothing to do with the spectrum.

00:51:30.339 --> 00:51:33.740
There is a thing where the hotter something
gets, the bluer the color is.

00:51:33.740 --> 00:51:40.020
It's nowhere near hot enough to be blue. It's
a chemical bluingness that creates that. More

00:51:40.020 --> 00:51:42.980
answer maybe than you wanted, but there you
go.

